<paragraph id="8BE236F59D6EFFD9FC87FB9C351BFA47" blockId="18.[813,1420,1138,1430]" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">
<emphasis id="B929EAE79D6EFFD9FC87FB9C32F5FB5B" bold="true" box="[813,974,1138,1162]" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">Identification.</emphasis>
This species is characterized by having short stems and internodes, intact, persistent and cucculate cataphylls, petioles usually ribbed, pendent inflo- rescences, and lilac, tapered and slender spadices. In the field, this species can be confused with 
<taxonomicName id="4C5D4D769D6EFFD9FB59FB163539FAE0" authority="Engl. ex K. Krause" authorityName="K. Krause" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Anthurium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="18" pageNumber="669" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ramonense">
<emphasis id="B929EAE79D6EFFD9FB59FB1634B7FAC1" box="[1267,1420,1272,1296]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">A. ramonense</emphasis>
Engl. ex K. Krause
</taxonomicName>
and with juvenile individuals of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5D4D769D6EFFD9FADEFAF43537FA82" authority="Guillaumin" authorityName="Guillaumin" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Anthurium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="18" pageNumber="669" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="michelii">
<emphasis id="B929EAE79D6EFFD9FADEFAF432B8FA82" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">A. michelii</emphasis>
Guillaumin
</taxonomicName>
, but both differs because they lack cucculate cataphylls (see the additional differences in the notes on both species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C347657E9D6EFFD9FC87FA413543F8E6" pageId="18" pageNumber="669" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BE236F59D6EFFD9FC87FA413543F8E6" blockId="18.[812,1420,1455,1847]" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">
<emphasis id="B929EAE79D6EFFD9FC87FA41356BFA19" bold="true" box="[813,1104,1455,1480]" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">Distribution and ecology.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="F34A76659D6EFFD9FBF3FA4135FEFA16" box="[1113,1221,1455,1479]" name="Colombia" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F34A76659D6EFFD9FB7AFA5E3470FA16" box="[1232,1355,1455,1480]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F34A76659D6EFFD9FAFCFA5E3243FA38" name="Guatemala" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F34A76659D6EFFD9FC21FA3F32CCFA38" box="[907,1015,1489,1513]" name="Honduras" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">Honduras</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F34A76659D6EFFD9FBA1FA3F3564FA38" box="[1035,1119,1489,1513]" name="Mexico" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F34A76659D6EFFD9FBD8FA3F35DEFA38" box="[1138,1253,1489,1513]" name="Nicaragua" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">Nicaragua</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="F34A76659D6EFFD9FA85FA3F34B3FA39" box="[1327,1416,1489,1512]" name="Panama" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">Panama</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C5D4D769D6EFFD9FC87FA1C32CCF9DB" box="[813,1015,1522,1546]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Anthurium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="18" pageNumber="669" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="salvinii">
<emphasis id="B929EAE79D6EFFD9FC87FA1C32CCF9DB" box="[813,1015,1522,1546]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">Anthurium salvinii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a fairly common species on Cerro Pirre. It grows along semideciduous and evergreen forests, from 
<quantity id="4CA59B109D6EFFD9FC34F9DB351AF99C" box="[926,1057,1589,1613]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.45" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="18" pageNumber="669" unit="m" value="445.0" valueMax="800.0" valueMin="90.0">
90 to 
<specimenCount id="9D5BFD7C9D6EFFD9FC70F9DB351AF99C" box="[986,1057,1589,1613]" pageId="18" pageNumber="669" type="generic">800 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. It is usual to observe this species as an epiphyte; however, it can grow as terrestrial or on rocks (epilitic). Its massively conglomerate roots and the arrangement of leaves in rosettes, allow it to accumulate detritus and moisture, as litter-trapping plants (see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFCC4B049D6EFFD9FC87F933355EF925" author="Zona S &amp; Christenhusz MJM" box="[813,1125,1756,1781]" pageId="18" pageNumber="669" pagination="554 - 586" refId="ref41351" refString="Zona S, Christenhusz MJM (2015) Litter-trapping plants: filterfeeders of the plant kingdom. Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society 179: 554 - 586. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / boj. 12346" type="journal article" year="2015">Zona and Christenhusz 2015</bibRefCitation>
). Probably, this mechanism allows the plant to establish itself successfully and grow in dry soils with few nutrients.
</paragraph>
